   President Bush, filling a key overseas post, has decided to nominate a former CIA officer as ambassador to China, sources said Wednesday.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The choice is James R. Lilley, a career intelligence officer who served as CIA station chief in China when Bush headed the U.S. liaison office there in 1974-75.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Lilley, 60, was born in China, the son of an American oilman working there.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   For the last three years, Lilley served as U.S. ambassador to South Korea.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
